> Q18. Does this trend look similar for the 2020 dataset?

```{r}
abdata.21 <- abdata %>% filter(dataset == "2021_dataset")

abdata.21 %>% 
  filter(isotype == "IgG",  antigen == "PT") %>%
  ggplot() +
    aes(x=planned_day_relative_to_boost,
        y=MFI_normalised,
        col=infancy_vac,
        group=subject_id) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_line() +
    geom_vline(xintercept=0, linetype="dashed") +
    geom_vline(xintercept=14, linetype="dashed") +
  labs(title="2021 dataset IgG PT",
       subtitle = "Dashed lines indicate day 0 (pre-boost) and 14 (apparent peak levels)")


```
Yes, the trend looks similar for the 2020 dataset. In both datasets, antibody levels increase after the booster and appear to peak around day 14, then gradually decrease over time. The individuals who received the wP vaccine also tend to show higher antibody levels compared to those who received the aP vaccine, which follows the same general pattern seen in the earlier dataset.

